  "prompt": "Are there statutes that address money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, there are several statutes that address money laundering in the United States:\n\n1. Federal Statutes:\n- Bank Secrecy Act (BSA)\n- Money Laundering Control Act of 1986\n- Anti-Money Laundering Act of 2020\n- USA PATRIOT Act\n\n2. Key Provisions:\n- 18 U.S. Code \u00a7 1956 (Money laundering criminal offenses)\n- 18 U.S. Code \u00a7 1957 (Monetary transactions in criminally derived property)\n\n3. Regulatory Agencies Involved:\n- Financial Crimes Enforcement Network (FinCEN)\n- Internal Revenue Service (IRS)\n- Department of Justice (DOJ)\n\n4. State-Level Statutes:\nMany states also have their own money laundering laws that complement federal statutes\n\n5. International Cooperation:\nThe U.S. works with international organizations like FATF (Financial Action Task Force) to combat global money laundering\n\nThese statutes generally aim to:\n- Criminalize financial transactions involving proceeds from illegal activities\n- Require financial institutions to report suspicious transactions\n- Establish reporting and record-keeping requirements\n- Impose significant criminal and civil penalties for violations",
